## General Instructions

- Never use other design systems or UI libraries such as Material UI, Chakra, etc.
- Never use other CSS frameworks such as Tailwind or SASS.
- Use CSS Modules for styling.
- Rely on the design system and avoid custom styling/components/icons as much as possible.
- ALWAYS read the relevant custom builder rules first before implementation.
- Do not hardcode typography-related CSS unless necessary, you should use IDS design tokens when possible.
- When building from a Figma design, explicitly code every intentional styling decision from the Figma design. Never assume browser defaults or implicit behavior will match the design intent. When in doubt, declare it in CSS.
- Prefer IDS icons over hardcoded SVGs whenever possible.

## Architecture Rules

### Component Usage

- Use `@ids-ts/*` components directly in JSX without creating wrapper components
- Only use `@ids-ts/*` component packages that are listed in the "Components available" section below
- For any @ids-ts/* component you want to use or need info for, make sure to read the corresponding builder rules file to understand usage and props
- In component rules, the props definition should generally trump other texts in the same file if they conflict
- If the @ids-ts/* component you want to use is not yet installed and added to package.json, you should always immediately install it using `yarn add @ids-ts/<component-name>` (no aliasing needed â€” packages resolve directly from the Intuit npm registry)
- When importing an `@ids-ts/*` component, always import its CSS file as well: `import '@ids-ts/<component>/dist/main.css'`
- If a needed pattern/component is not available in `@ids-ts/*`, create one and make sure to note the gap to the user

### Styling Approach

- CSS Modules for component-specific styles
- Design tokens for colors, spacing, typography, borders
- Flexbox/Grid for layout, not absolute positioning unless needed for a specific use-case
- Media queries for responsive design

